nodes.documentation:
@dev Library for managing
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_(abstract_data_type)[sets] of primitive
types.
 * Sets have the following properties:
 * - Elements are added, removed, and checked for existence in constant time
(O(1)).
- Elements are enumerated in O(n). No guarantees are made on the ordering.
 * As of v2.5.0, only `address` sets are supported.
 * Include with `using EnumerableSet for EnumerableSet.AddressSet;`.
 * _Available since v2.5.0._
 * @author Alberto Cuesta Cañada
nodes.name: EnumerableSet

typeDescriptions.typeString: function (struct EnumerableSet.AddressSet storage pointer,address) view returns (bool)

nodes.documentation:
@dev Add a value to a set. O(1).
Returns false if the value was already in the set.
nodes.name: add

typeDescriptions.typeString: function (struct EnumerableSet.AddressSet storage pointer,address) view returns (bool)

nodes.documentation:
@dev Removes a value from a set. O(1).
Returns false if the value was not present in the set.
nodes.name: remove

nodes.documentation: @dev Returns true if the value is in the set. O(1).
nodes.name: contains

nodes.documentation:
@dev Returns an array with all values in the set. O(N).
Note that there are no guarantees on the ordering of values inside the
array, and it may change when more values are added or removed.
WARNING: This function may run out of gas on large sets: use {length} and
{get} instead in these cases.
nodes.name: enumerate

nodes.documentation: @dev Returns the number of elements on the set. O(1).
nodes.name: length

nodes.documentation:
@dev Returns the element stored at position `index` in the set. O(1).
Note that there are no guarantees on the ordering of values inside the
array, and it may change when more values are added or removed.
    * Requirements:
    * - `index` must be strictly less than {length}.
nodes.name: get
